 more conventional films aimed at the public at large remains underexplored. By combining close textual analysis of films with the study of their cultural context, this book argues that fictional cinema at large addressed predominantly middle-class audiences, offering both reflective and divergent views on social reality that enriched the cultural arena in which Argentineans could reflect on their past, their daily life, and their relationship with the other. In this sense cinema helped Argentine people to learn to live in democracy. Santiago Oyarzabal is Associate Fellow in Hispanic Studies at the University of Warwick.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aCulture in motion pictures. 0aMotion picturesxHistoryzArgentina. 0aMotion picturesxSocial aspectszArgentina. 0aMotion pictureszArgentinaxHistory. 0aNational characteristics, Argentine, in motion pictures. 0aSocial classes in motion pictures. 4aFilm & Theatre. 4aHispanic Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh  aArgentine Cinema.  aArgentinean society.  acontemporary issues.  acrisis representation.  acultural change.  acultural reflection.  amiddle-class audiences.  anational identity.  asocial discourse.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311143101740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782046578423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782046578/original  a978-3-11-143101-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles